             rdfs:label "creep percentage permanent elongation value"@en ;
             skos:definition "A creep percentage permanent elongation value is a scalar value specification that specifies the value of the percentage permanent elongation realized in a creep testing process. It quantifies the irreversible axial deformation of the specimen after unloading relative to its original gauge length. It appears as a numeric value expressed as a percentage (e.g., \"13.8%\"), typically found in the creep properties table or post-test characterization section of a scientific paper, and explicitly refers to the permanent elongation measured on the target creep test piece." .


