                                                  ]
                             ] ;
             rdfs:label "stress exponent value"@en ;
             skos:definition "A stress exponent value is a scalar value specification that specifies the value of the stress exponent realized in a creep testing process. It quantifies the sensitivity of the creep rate to applied stress, as defined by the Norton power-law creep model (ε̇ ∝ σⁿ). It appears as a dimensionless numeric value (e.g., \"n = 5\", \"n = 10\"), typically found in the creep analysis, model fitting, or discussion section of a scientific paper, and explicitly refers to the stress exponent derived from the target creep testing data." .


