             rdfs:label "creep activation energy value"@en ;
             skos:definition "A creep activation energy value is a scalar value specification that specifies the value of the activation energy which is a process attribute of a creep testing process. It quantifies the energy barrier governing thermally activated creep deformation mechanisms, commonly derived from Arrhenius-type analysis. It appears as a numeric value with a unit of energy per mole (e.g., \"276 kJ/mol\", \"309 kJ/mol\"), typically found in the creep analysis, Arrhenius plot, or discussion section of a scientific paper, and explicitly refers to the activation energy characterizing the dominant creep mechanism in the target creep testing process." .


